Lest we forget! 
Heroes are not always the ones with only two feet. Sometimes the heroic acts are only a simple act of kindness.

In 1987, Berners in Canada were a rare sight. Dean and I were walking one of our Berners down Whyte Avenue in Edmonton. We strolled past an outdoor cafe and we heard "a Sennenhund" coming from one of the tables. Most people at the time could not identify a Bernese Mountain Dog let alone by their Swiss-German name. An elderly man and his daughter were sitting at the table, she asked if we could come over so her dad could see Cliff.

I was concerned that Cliff would be a bit too rambunctious for the elderly man but we brought him over. The man slowly reached down and wrapped his arms around Cliff's neck and buried his face in his coat. After hugging Cliff for a unusually long time, the gentleman sat back up with tears streaming down his face.

Once he regained his composure, he retold the stories of his wartime experiences.

His platoon in Europe used dogs to transport ammunition, food and medical supplies. Several of those dogs were Bernese Mountain Dogs.

He had lots of stories of his fellow soldiers and the dogs that served alongside. But the one story that stood out the most was that the only times he remembered being warm enough to sleep was when one of the Berners would sleep with him. Safe and warm, even during the horrors of war.

He held on to this love and gratitude to the Bernese Mountain Dog for all those years.
